SPECIES COMMENTS: 16 were seen flying east to west over Hwy 99 near Book Family Farm (just south of Durham-Pentz Rd). The rest were seen flying east to west over Hwy 70 north of the Thermalito Forebay. I was 15 minutes late to work today - I normally see 1 to 10 bald eagles on my drive from Chico to Oroville, but thus is the first time I've seen 21. Of course, if I pulled over & watched for awhile, I'd probably see more. I think they are flying from their roost on Lake Oroville to their foraging areas.

Sunny, few clouds, Beaufort 2. Rain the previous night.  We started from the Valle Vista parking area, where we noted many pines had been cut, and redwoods planted near the entrance.  Some oaks are also being planted in the meadow areas, and new bluebird boxes have been installed.  Several of the boxes were being contested by Tree Swallows.  Starlings were nesting in snags left along the road, and a pair of kestrels seemed to be exploring the area.  Walking down the Kings Canyon loop, we turned off to the left to go through a small pine forest full of birdsong - including House and Bewick's Wrens, Spotted Towhee, many Acorn Woodpeckers, Orange-crowned and Wilson's Warblers.  Arriving at the bridge over Moraga Creek, a few of the group spotted Wood Ducks hurrying away.  On the east side of the bridge is a large Twinberry bush, which is a magnet for hummingbirds.  We finally located a Rufous Hummingbird, and even saw the notched R2 through a scope as it perched on a wire.  A little further on, a pair of Bewick's Wrens were taking nesting material to some small stumps under bushes, and a Red-breasted Sapsucker, hopefully heading for the mountains, burst out of the tall pines.  The reservoir, with some water after the rains, had a variety of ducks and waterbirds noted in the list.  Five swallow species, some recent arrivals, were noted.  A young Bald Eagle sat in a madrone on the other side of the water, and eventually flew, showing some white underwing coverts.  We continued up the trail to the entry of the forest, then turned around.  On the return, we came across a very sick Bobcat, and authorities were noted.  Other mammals noted were deer, Brush Rabbit, squirrel.
SPECIES COMMENTS: first year

TRIP COMMENTS: On our way south, Paul Lehman, Barbara Carlson, and I stopped briefly at the overlook above the dam at Tinemaha Reservoir to see if we could find anything on the lake following a brief rain squall.  As has been typical of my visits to this lake, we saw only a few birds and nothing of exceptional interest during a quick scan from inside the vehicle as we parked at the overlook on the hillside just west of the dam.  There was a full and relatively dense overcast, drizzle, some wind, and a temperature of 57º F (based on the thermometer in Paul's vehicle).  8:13-8:16 am.
SPECIES COMMENTS: (an adult perched in a snag over the middle of the lake was clearly a large raptor with a white head and a dark brown body, but as I recall it was a bit far to clearly distinguish the yellow bill or the white tail)

TRIP COMMENTS: Spent most of the time in the southern half of Burris Basin (including Anaheim Coves Park), and spent a good part of the time viewing the Tern Island (where Least and Forster's terns, and Black Skimmers have been nesting).  Weather:  Overcast through mid-day, then sunny (a bit hazy, 20-25% cloud cover), ~70 deg. (F), 3-6 mph SW winds.----Abbreviations used:  ACP = Anaheim Coves Park;  BB = Burris Basin;  TI = Tern Island. (TI is a 2.4 acre island created in the middle of Burris Basin, as a potential nesting site to replace nesting habitat for the two terns and skimmers that was removed as part of the Burris Basin Reconfiguration Project, designed by the Orange County Water District to increase water storage capacity, as well as aid percolation of water into the groundwater system in this part of the county.)
SPECIES COMMENTS: An immature bird, circling somewhat high up, just east of BB, when I first saw it.  Slowly moved in towards the north end BB, but didn't linger long and disappeared back to the northeast.  First heard "yapping" of American Avocets, and alarm type calls of American Crows, and saw this odd mixed group of bird up harassing a large, mostly dark raptor over the east side of BB.  For a half-second I thought they were harassing a Turkey Vulture, but immediately then noticed this was a Bald Eagle!  Mostly dark, but lots of white mottling on the underparts (breast/belly), and on underwings.  The huge size of the bird was impressive when compared to AMAVs and AMCRs that had flown up to intercept the large bird of prey.  The first BAEA I've seen at Burris since back in maybe the late 1990s or early 2000s when up to two subadult BAEAs hung around the Burris and upper SAR area (often could be seen from Burris, when they'd typically be perched in Eucs along the SAR, just north or south of Lincoln, or atop a power pole).

TRIP COMMENTS: Nancy Kenyon & Neal Anderson
SPECIES COMMENTS: Similar species is probably an Osprey since both species--have white on their heads & dark bodies. However, the Osprey has a white breast & belly while the Bald--Eagle has a solid white head and neck and a dark breast and belly. the Osprey has black markings on--its head while the Bald Eagle’s head is pure white.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Observed from below at an approximate distance of 75 feet as it circled low over the 15 Freeway just west of the Corona Fishing Lake.    As compared to nearby adult Red-tailed Hawk, this bird was at least 1/3 size larger.   Mostly dark, except that it had a white and dark mixed pattern along both the leading and trailing edge of the wings, as well as a white and dark mixed pattern across the belly and lower breast.  The tail was white with a dark terminal band.   The fully feathered head was also partially white mixed with dark brown/black.  Possible 2nd year bird.

This is a historical record where I know the specific and sometimes general location, date and species. I will enter “x” for each species seen unless my field notes give me an actual number in which case I’ll add that. Usually there will be no data on effort, number of participants or hours of search. This was a trip that began late in 2013 and finished early in January 2014. Each site visited will have its own eBird list. This day was a driving day to get across the state while visiting several locations that were visited a few days before to get certain species for 2014. The trip left Gonzales and crossed over on Gloria Road with short stops into Pinnacles National Park, Panoche Valley and the Mineral Hot Springs which might be called Mercy Hot Springs. Then in the dark to Bakersfield.

Close view, mostly ventral and wing-on. ID'd by shape, huge size, mostly dark color, mottling of white on underwings and belly, absence of white on head or tail (so SA or Juv), long head with a huge bill, relatively short tail. Given the amount of white on belly, it looked like an SA1 or SA2. Headed west towards Land's End.
crossing the park to the north being attacked by red tailed hawks

This was clearly an adult bald eagle. the only other bird comparable in size this day was a turkey vulture. The turkey vulture flies in seeming "off-balance" action, often tilting as it soars. This bird soared with wings fixed and firm in flight. The V-shaped dihedral of a turkey vulture was also missing from this bird, although we only saw its underside. The sheer size of this bird, although already about 200' off the ground when we first saw it, was clearly quite large with broad, dark-undersided wings. Moreover, it was clear, at this distance, that the bird had a white head and white tail. The head seemed large and the tail broad.----Though not reported on this list, a turkey vulture (or vultures) did visit the El Polin/Greater Tennessee Hollow area a few times that day.----Seen by a few of us who were already equipped to lead two separate BioBlitz walks. First ID'd by an anonymous female park visitor less than an hour before. A few of us were discussing her claim when suddenly Lishka Arata looks up and exclaims, "There it is!" Indeed, there it was. Three or four of us (perhaps more) had good looks at it for only a few seconds before it disappeared out of view behind pines. It probably continued moving in the direction toward the Marina district. Incredible!

A very large, dorsally dark/blackish raptor, flying with very heavy/ponderous wing beats. "Grizzled" pale below indicating a sub adult bird, head and tail dark. Head and tail appearing about equal length and wings held flat/slightly dropped at the tips in glide.  2nd in the fall migration period '14 from this site, HY passing over in early August.rare and  increasing as fly-over in SF  with  establishing of breeding territories in several nearby counties

TRIP COMMENTS:
This was a class field trip that I was leading for the American River Natural History Association. It was our second field trip of the three-lecture/field trip series. This was a make-up due to the rains that washed out our planned trip on 8 February. Dan Tankersley ably assisted me with this large group. Weather was perfect with clear skies, temperatures reaching into the low 70's and only a slight breeze. We started at Farmington, drove east to Buckman Road, then on up north Waverly to Flood Road with a short side trip to the corral near the T-intersection. From there we could see the large landfill and mass of gulls and ravens, but we did not travel to this location. We exited on Flood Road ending the count at the intersection of Wallace-Bellota Road.
Submitted from BirdLog NA for iOS, version 1.7.1

SPECIES COMMENTS: There were 3 of us who observed the bald eagle soar & fly above the dam & the fish hatchery parking lot.  We tried to take photos but none were very good.  All 3 of us have small digital cameras.  This was about 10:10 am just after we arrived.  It was the 2nd bird we saw. The first bird was a Northern Mockingbird.  This was a mature bald eagle.  The white head & tail were very distinctive.  No mistake.  All 3 of us were surprised & excited to see one this time of year.  The eagle soared above us for about 2 minutes than went back over the dam .

LOCALITY: Santa Cruz / Santa Rosa passage (SBA Co.)
Santa Cruz / Santa Rosa passage (SBA Co.)
TRIP COMMENTS: Fifrth leg of a 10-hour pelagic trip on the Condor Express out of the Santa Barbara Harbor. Birds on this list were those seen in the Santa Cruz Passage. This list starts with us leaving the big Black-vented Shearwater flock and heading south through the passage. There were more shearwaters on the north side and another flock of 200 birds in the middle of the passage. We checked Gull Island for Boobies to no avail. However, we did see a Bald Eagle there and a Southern Sea Otter. 25% cover of high, thin clouds, 10 knot breeze from the west, 3 foot swell through the passage. Leaders were David Pereksta, Todd McGrath, Adam Searcy, Bernardo Alps, and Hugh Ranson.

SPECIES COMMENTS: I'mmature. 1-2 yrs old.

LOCALITY: Santa Cruz Island -- nearshore Prisoner's to Platt's

TRIP COMMENTS:
I rented a 6 hp motor boat to find where shorebirds and ducks hang out and how we might detect them best on the Cachuma Christmas Bird Count. Weather: stiff wind from the west northwest dark clouds, looks like rain coming, temp in the 60s so not very cold. I did not cover the western end of the lake but rather peaked into Johnson day, Cachuma Bay, and Santa Cruz Bay, as well as the east shoreline. The eastern shore is currently at 34.56799 -119.92000 (WGS 84). Far more ducks were tucked away at the East End than anywhere else on the lake including Santa Cruz Bay. Wind and the awkwardnes of driving the boat in the wind made observations difficult. Perhaps 500 ducks were at the E end that I did not see well enough to count.

Old Shasta, off Rock Creek Road, Walker Terrace home yard and feeder list. Lived there from 1985-2018 to the Carr Fire burn out, 33 years worth. List has 2013 and 2014 written on the form. Feeding regular mixed bird seed, sunflower seed, cracker corn, and thistle seed. 8-10 Hummer feeders. 21 seed feeders and areas, 2 suet feeders, and 1 water drip.  Many notable species, Mountain Quail, Northern Goshawk, Merlin’s, Prairie Falcons, Spotted Owl, Swa-whet Owl, Costa’s Hummingbirds several times, Lewis’s Woodpecker, aNothern Shrike hiding in the bushes grabbing hummers to eat, Clarke’s Nutcrackers calling and flying around, a pure Yellow-shafted Flicker several times, Purple Martins, Pygmy Nuthatches, House Wren, Blue-gray Gnatcatcher, Townsend’s Solitaire, Swainson’s Thrush, the county’s first Collared Dove, Varied Thrush, Townsend’s Warbler, Hermit Warbler, Yellow-breasted Chat, Chipping Sparrow, Lark Sparrow on 5/7/2003, Lincoln’s Sparrows, White-throated Sparrows, Harris’s Sparrow in breeding Plumage, Lazuli Bunting, Great-tailed Grackle on 7/14/2013 with pix, Cassin’s Finches often, Rec Crossbills, Lawrence’s Goldfinch male with pix, Evening Grosbeaks fairly regularly, Allen’s Hummingbird with tail spread pix, Broad-tailed Hummingbirds with upper tail pix, Red-napped Sapsucker, Gray Flycatcher, and Rose-breasted Grosbeak.  Notes say 145 total  species; 143 as of 2/14/2013, 144 as of 7/14/2013, 145 as of 3/18/2014.

Lake Kaweah.  After a call this late morning from Kim Kuska about more loons at Lake Kaweah Priscilla and I visited there from 1:30p-2:45p.  We found the same loons we had seen on the 21st – a Common Loon and two Pacific Loons. Slightly better views today made us feel that the Common Loon was a first winter bird and the Pacific Loons were one first winter and one winter adult. We also enjoyed a confrontation between an Osprey and a Bald Eagle. The eagle forced the Osprey to drop its catch into the lake, which go away. All together there were three adult Bald Eagles.

TRIP COMMENTS: One of the Red-tail hawks we have here was diving on the eagle. I have never seen a Red-tail look so small!
SPECIES COMMENTS: This was a second year bird. We have breeding pairs here in the Ojai Vally at Lake Casitas and at Lake Chachuma in Santa Barbara county. The bird had a dark head and beak. Underneath the wings had a lot of white in the coverts and some in the secondaries and primaries. The breast was dark and the belly mostly whitish. The base of the tail showed some white with the rest dark. Wings were very long. One of the resident Red-tails we have here was diving on the eagle and I have never seen a Red-tail look so small!

TRIP COMMENTS: Santa Barbara Audubon field trip to Naval Base Ventura County. The tide was very high upon arrival (6.2' dropping at a rate of -0.1/hour) and the lagoon near the causeway and at the mouth was completely inundated. We started at the mouth where we scoped the lagoon and did a brief seawatch. We then checked the night-heron roost, the ballfields, and continued around the perimeter to west end of the base. Later in the morning we circled back and birded the lagoon as the tide was dropping and shorebirds were moving out on the exposed flats.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Blue tag with white #67
